text: Alright, time to pick this thing apart.  First of all, the video description says this: "He has no memory of the outside world other than strange dreams about a mysterious organization known as W.C.K.D." Okay, first of all, it's W.I.C.K.E.D., not W.C.K.D. And second, that's completely wrong. His only memory is his name (which, according to this trailer, he doesn't remember in the movie) and he knows nothing about W.I.C.K.E.D. until he goes through The Changing. He doesn't even know the name until he sees it on the back of a beetle blade.  Now for the trailer's inconsistencies with the book (not that all of these really matter a whole lot, but still): 1) The Box shouldn't have holes in the floor, walls, and ceiling. 2) As revealed in the prologue of The Kill Order, the Box shaft is actually only two or three stories high, and the shaking and movements of the Box are merely designed to manipulate the victim into thinking that the trip is a really long way up. The Box shaft is shown here as being really tall. 3) In the book, Gally isn't the first to greet Thomas, and regardless of who it is, no one jumps in the Box; they lower a rope and bring Thomas up on it. 4) "Can you tell me a name?" "I can't remember anything." Wrong! In the book, Thomas knows his name. 5) Why are all their names carved into the wall? 6) What's up with the Doors here? Where are the metal rods? 7) The miniature model of the Maze wasn't a thing in the book. And the Maze isn't circular; it's supposed to be a perfect square. 8) Lots of stuff in the Maze shown here that definitely wasn't in the book. Like the laser scanner. 9) What's that metal thing Minho is holding at 1:01? 10) Gally doesn't sound mean enough. 11) When Teresa shows up, she's supposed to be in a coma. 12) At 1:19, is he on top of the Maze? Nope. Not supposed to be a thing. 13) The walls change while the Doors close, not while Thomas and Minho are running through the Maze. And they're supposed to be super thick slabs of metal, not these slim turning panel things. 14) At 1:24, is Gally... drowning? I don't remember that happening in the book. 15) At the end. The Maze crumbling and falling apart and whatnot... not supposed to happen until book 3.  LOTS of inconsistency. But it looks well-made, and I'm still way-excited to see it. It's just that this is one of my favorite books ever and I want this movie to do it justice.

text: I'd like to share something with anybody who thinks Maze Runner is a Hunger Games rip-off. The Maze Runner was written years ago, well before Hunger Games even came out. text: Listen. This might be a VERY long comment. There is a maze, and in the middle of the maze, there is a huge box called the Glade. The boys live there. That's right. Only BOYS. Each month a new boy comes. The boy's memories have been erased. THey don't know how to talk, walk, crawl - ect. The only thing they know is their names. The main character's name? Thomas. Each person has a job. THe most dangerous job is the runner's job. You see, on each side of the maze there is two huge doors. At the first light of dawn in the morning, the doors open. If you go into the doors, you go to the maze. The maze is huge and dangerous. The runners have to run into the maze and calculate it for a way out. The maze is the only way out of the Glade. At night, the doors close. The runners must return to the Glade before the doors close. Why can't they just spend the night in the maze? YOU CAN'T. At nighttime, these horrible robotic THINGS come out, and they kill you. Nobody has ever survived a night in the maze. If you're by the doors when they shut, you get crushed. They're made of pure stone. When i said each month a boy comes, well, on day a girl comes. Her name is Teresa. She is the first girl ever to arrive in the Glade. Since that moment she came, everything changed. I know all of this because I read the first book, and i'm moving on to the second book. I don't want to spoil to much. Thanks for sticking around and reading this comment!Â

The PROJECT (as it is every book that's going to come to the "big screen") MUST BE APPLICABLE TO THE MEDIUM!!! text: For someone like me that hadn't read the books before seeing the movie, I thought the movie was amazing. If it were never a book and someone came up with this exact screenplay then it would have been one of the best movies released in 2014 yet. But because so many of you have read the book, you're comparing the film to the books, therefor making a judgement on the creativity of production. Everyone knows they can't add or put the exact scenes of every book into a movie. Even with the authors permission, it would still be copyright and they obviously don't want to take away the credibility of the book. But, that being said, the movie has made me want to read the books and I'm excited for the rest of the movies to come out in the future :D

text: Though there seems to be an equal amount of top comments saying they hate/are disappointed with the movie, or that they loved it I just want to go on record saying I liked this movie a lot. Let me tell you why; without spoiling much, it had a pretty good plot, not the best, but pretty good, and THERE IS NO ROMANCE in the entire movie, which I love. I'm not a big fan of romance, and the hunger games, divergent and stuff like that I haven't watched for that Â reason and others, so I was very pleased when I watched this, though that may me just me. Certain parts which were, or I think were, suppose to tug my "heart strings" didn't really do it that much, while others got me pretty hard. The costumes were nice, and I think the CGI was great. Also it's a pretty good stand-alone movie if you life cliff-hanger endings. True, there were one or two cliches, but all things said I'd definitely watch this again. Â   Just my rambling but hope that helped someone make their decision about the movie! ^^

text: The book is much better than the film, but this is still a great film nonetheless. I would definitely rank it high among the other top box office hits, but it still fell short in my expectations. I'm really hoping for a great delivery on the second film, because the second book was definitely better than the first. The acting and visual effects are very top notch, but the film needs to be slowed down to add character development. The book actually made the reader become attached to the characters so that if/when one died, it was big. The movie was so rushed that I had a hard time figuring out who I liked and who I didn't like. The plot was also shifted massively for whatever reason, so there was no "OH COOL!!!" moments, it was more like "Wow, this guy got lucky. Which made everyone else get lucky".
